🚀 DevOps Interview Series | Day 4/7 – Kubernetes

☸️ Kubernetes Production Interview Scenario

Interviewer:

"A deployment was successful, but all the Pods are in the CrashLoopBackOff state. How would you troubleshoot the issue?"

My Approach

1️⃣ Check the pod status

kubectl get pods -A

2️⃣ Describe the failing pod

kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

Check Events.
Verify image pull status.
Look for probe failures.

3️⃣ Check application logs

kubectl logs <pod-name>
If the container keeps restarting:
kubectl logs <pod-name> --previous

4️⃣ Verify the Deployment configuration

kubectl describe deployment <deployment-name>
kubectl get deployment

5️⃣ Check ConfigMaps and Secrets

kubectl get configmap
kubectl get secrets
Verify required environment variables exist.

6️⃣ Verify resource limits

kubectl top pod
kubectl describe node
Check whether the Pod is getting OOMKilled.
Verify CPU and Memory requests/limits.

7️⃣ Verify image availability
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
Ensure the image exists.
Verify image tag and registry credentials.

Key Takeaway

Most CrashLoopBackOff issues are caused by:

Application startup failures

Incorrect environment variables

Missing Secrets or ConfigMaps

Liveness/Readiness probe failures

Insufficient CPU or Memory

A structured troubleshooting approach helps identify the root cause much faster than simply restarting Pods.

