Production Terraform Scenario: EC2 Instance Deleted Manually – What Happens Next?
Recently, while preparing for DevOps interviews, I came across an interesting Terraform production scenario.
Scenario
Your infrastructure is managed using Terraform.
Terraform code:

resource "aws_instance" "web" {
 ami = "ami-123"
 instance_type = "t3.micro"
}

Everything is working fine until someone manually deletes the EC2 instance from the AWS Console.
At this point:
✅ Terraform State File still contains the EC2 resource
❌ Actual EC2 instance no longer exists in AWS
What Happens When You Run terraform plan?
Terraform compares:
Desired State (Terraform code)
Actual State (AWS Infrastructure)
It detects that the EC2 instance is missing and reports infrastructure drift.
Example output:
Plan: 1 to add, 0 to change, 0 to destroy

What Happens When You Run terraform apply?
Terraform automatically recreates the missing EC2 instance to bring the infrastructure back to the desired state defined in the code.
This demonstrates one of the biggest advantages of Infrastructure as Code (IaC):
✅ Drift Detection
✅ Infrastructure Recovery
✅ Consistency Across Environments
✅ Reduced Manual Errors
Key Learning
In production environments, Terraform should remain the single source of truth.
Manual changes through the AWS Console can introduce infrastructure drift and unexpected behavior.
The best practice is:
👉 Make changes through Terraform code
👉 Run terraform plan
👉 Review changes
👉 Apply using terraform apply
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
I just lost 2 hours to a space. Literally. One extra space 🙃😅 

Today I was containerizing a Go application. Image built perfectly. But the container kept crashing on every startup with:

exec: "./product-catalog": no such file or directory

I went through everything:
✅ Multi-stage build artifacts — fine
✅ Go binary compiled — fine
✅ File permissions — fine
✅ Runtime image contents — fine

The binary was RIGHT THERE. I could see it in the image.

After 2 hours I finally looked closely at my ENTRYPOINT...

❌ ENTRYPOINT ["  ./product-catalog"]  ← what I had
✅ ENTRYPOINT ["./product-catalog"]    ← what it should be

A single accidental space before the path. That's it. That's the whole issue.

Fixed it, rebuilt, container started instantly. 🤦‍♂️

💡 If your Docker container fails at startup despite a clean build — before doing ANYTHING else, just read your ENTRYPOINT character by character. You might be surprised.

The most expensive bugs are often the smallest ones.
